GIRALDUS
CAMBRENSIS.

Giraldus
expostulated
with
the
discordant
pair
so
persua

sively
and
affectionately,
that
a
complete
reconciliation

followed,
and
they
lived
a
united
couple
ever
after.
A
strict

diciplinarian,
perhaps
a
shade
too
much
so,
he
was
a
man
of

his
word.
His
own
parishioners
at
Nangle
having
incurred

excommunication
for
the
deadly
sin
of
keeping
back
the

tithes,
and
repented
and
paid
up,
he
promised
to
absolve

them
on
a
certain
day, — the
day
came,
and
with
it
a
tremen

dous
tempest,
which
made
travelling,
as
travelling
was
in

those
days,
positively
dangerous :
however,
he
had
passed
his

word,
and
go
he
would
;
and
he
went.
As
to
personal
fear,
he

did
not
know
what
it
was, — I
suppose
that
no
Welshman

does.

the
contest
for
St.
David's,

was
a

marked
man,

the
royal
displeasure

shape
it

parts

Cardiganshire,
a
mes

all
